ver enjoys a level of impunity that decreases road safety for other users and cyclists are disproportionately penalised</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">National safety campaign showing dangers to cyclists of driving too close at different speeds</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tackle the current tendency toward</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s negativity even discrimination against cyclists e.g. show cyclists as part of the vision of a future where urban space is truly shared; children can play outside and walk/cycle/scoot to school; air is cleaner; outside space is safer for everyone; and the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> motor vehicle no longer dominates daily life etc. Without cyclists, there would be even more speed and therefore danger to pedestrians...cyclists are a natural traffic calming device! Possibly this would encourage the aggressive cyclist to be less of a me</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nace and more proud of their part in changing things for the better</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">..hopefully</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. When there is dedicated space for cyclists and cycling is for everyone, not just the foolhardy, then the need for aggression will dissipate. At the moment, though, the reaction</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to aggressive cycling, is disproportionate and detracts from the need to tackle dangerous driving</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">collect data from cyclists regarding their experience of being in danger on the road: under what conditions is this most likely e.g. when traffic lights chan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ge to green; at junctions etc</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">* </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> objection that this would hurt business is not, as far as I understand, the experience of other European countries that operate this strategy. Also, surely pedestrians and cyclists have for too long been forced to accep</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t a disproportionate responsibility for adaptation to the needs of motorised traffic.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At the end of the day, we would all hope to have outdoor space which children and the elderly can enjoy safely and without being in fear of their lives.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Thank you for do</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing your part in making this a reality.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:ita